in small intestine, complete faecal excretion","Formation in liver, direct excretion into urine","Formation in kidney, excretion in urine only"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe correct pathway involves \u003Cstrong\u003Eformation in the colon followed by majority reabsorption into portal circulation\u003C/strong\u003E. Intestinal bacteria reduce conjugated bilirubin to urobilinogen in the colon. About 80-90% of urobilinogen is reabsorbed into portal circulation and returned to the liver for re-excretion in the urine. A small portion (10-20%) is excreted in faeces as stercobilin..\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EFormation in liver, direct excretion into urine\u003C/strong\u003E - The liver does not form urobilinogen; it only processes it after intestinal formation\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EFormation in kidney, excretion in urine only\u003C/strong\u003E - Kidneys do not produce urobilinogen; they only filter small amounts from blood\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EFormation in small intestine, complete faecal excretion\u003C/strong\u003E - Formation occurs in the colon, not small intestine, and most is reabsorbed rather than excreted\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EFormation in stomach, equal urinary and faecal excretion\u003C/strong\u003E - Stomach lacks the bacterial flora needed for urobilinogen formation\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThis enterohepatic circulation of urobilinogen is important for maintaining normal bile pigment metabolism and preventing excessive loss of these compounds.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Urobilinogen is formed when intestinal bacteria reduce bilirubin to urobilinogen in the colon.","Most urobilinogen is reabsorbed via the portal circulation and excreted in the urine."],"references":["Tortora GJ, Derrickson BH, Burkett B, Peoples G, Dye D, Cooke J, et al. Principles of Anatomy and Physiology, 2nd Asia-Pacific Edition: John Wiley \u0026 Sons, Limited; 2019"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"55519"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17323"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"55519","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/55519"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-13T09:19:00+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-13T09:19:31+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10013"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"70057"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synonyms":null,"description":"Remember (identifying and retrieving information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"7"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"4928","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/4928"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udca9","name"